article.description: Becky Hammon scored a season-high 28 points and combined with Sophia Young to score San Antonio's final 24 points and the Silver Stars held off the Washington Mystics for a 83-75 win on Sunday.
article.headline: Hammon's season-high 28 lead Silver Stars past Mystics
article.linkText: Silver Stars' Hammon leads late push vs. Mystics
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- After watching the San Antonio Silver Stars' double-digit, second-half lead fade into a one-point deficit, Becky Hammon and Sophia Young got aggressive.

Hammon scored a season-high 28 points and combined with Young to score San Antonio's final 24 points and the Silver Stars held off the Washington Mystics for a 83-75 win on Sunday.

After the Mystics erased San Antonio's 12-point lead, Hammon hit a 3-pointer with 5:54 left to give the Western Conference-leading Silver Stars (12-6) a 63-61 lead. From there she and Young, who scored 23 points, had their way against the Mystics defense.

"We play smart, but we keep attacking and we keep the pressure on," Hammon said. "We are not sitting back trying to make mistakes. I think that is what has enabled us to win a lot of close games. We keep coming at ya."

The Silver Stars have won four straight games and nine of 11 overall.

Hammon, who did not score until 1:40 remained in the first half, scored 14 of her 21 second half points during the closing run and did so in nearly every conceivable way. When she was not slashing her way to the basket for tough angled layups, Hammon was connecting on four 3-point field goals. The WNBA's leading free throw shooter also went 10-for-10 from the free-throw line.

"I was just trying to be patient, take whatever was open," said Hammon, who added a game-high six assists. "A lot of times that is passing the ball for me. Other times its scoring."

Was there anything she did not do on the offensive end?

"I didn't dunk", said the smiling 5-6 guard, who scored a combined 48 points in two games against the Mystics this season.

"Becky is a great player. She knows how to put the ball in the goal," Mystics guard Alana Beard said. "She's a shooter. I think she has one of the most dangerous games around the goal. She goes in and puts that english on the ball and put the ball in.

Beard led the Mystics (6-11) with 20 points, including 18 in the second half. Rookie Crystal Langhorne scored a career-high 17 points and Taj McWilliams-Franklin added 15 points for the Mystics, who have dropped three straight games and failed to stop the Silver Stars offense down the stretch.

"Keep fighting, keep fighting," Beard said when asked what the Mystics can do to stop their current slide. "I don't doubt that everyone is playing hard and that we are playing with effort. I would never question that. But its a matter of us communicating and getting stops. We need stops."

Ann Wauters added 18 points for the Silver Stars, who completed a season sweep over the Mystics. They trailed 21-15 early in the second quarter, but took the lead as Wauters scored nine points during a 14-2 rally. Wauters hit 6 of 7 field-goal attempts in the first half and the Silver Stars led 36-28 at halftime.
